The Higgs shelled boson
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created a whole stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that this is Higgs.
We know without a shadow of doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be absolutely certain.
Let us assume, however, that this is the Higgs, since the chances of getting wrong seem slim, and let us see what this is about.
There is, in this world, a fatally unavoidable law that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
Even though particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: Pauli's principle of exclusion, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - that "state" consisting roughly in some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner there are good citizens named fermions, who obey the principle of Pauli wisely.
And in the other are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything - in any case, not for this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, depending on the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not approach here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
These bosons, it must be emphasized here, are not all as exotic as we might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" which is the "messager" of electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "dranges" the electromagnetic field in this precise place, a bit like a rock thrown into a pond.
From this "drangement" comes an electromagnetic wave (from light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore, one of the bosons "force carriers".
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, except that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disturbed" in order for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to reach very, very high energies, a bit as if it were a frozen pond, only a very large rock could ride the surface.
This is why it takes a huge particle accelerator like that of CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring of 27 km of circumference! - to reach such energies.
Analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between Higgs and mass.
Not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold on to a fridge.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while others (like photon, hold) don't.
Now, what can "bring" all this research, asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to examine any discrepancies between observations and predictions of the MS.
There are many who want to find them, because the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has huge deficiencies, offering no explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-oops!).
But we haven't found such discrepancies at CERN until now.
Impact
The impact of this research on Mr. and Mrs. All-the-World's daily lives is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be none.
Here: in the early 1960s, laser pioneers in Bell Laboratories had no suspicion of the revolution that their work would trigger.
They were sending scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, we have already told us the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 - initially the laser was rather seen as a "lab gandget".
Imagine...
And then, applications can also come from the entire instrumentation that surrounds the search.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his optical work.
This sensor, although not at all its original intent, now serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras in the world, and earned it the Nobel Prize in Physics 2009.
This does not mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it means that, really, we never know...
Palliative care - The best way to die...
With its Commission to Die in Dignity, Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate must resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this crucial area.
The Devoir tried to take a closer look at it.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that was eating him had left him with a two-year respite.
"They had given me five years to live, I did seven years," he said, half-figue half-raisin, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the previous day.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease does its work: a huge weakness that prevents it from going alone to the toilet, and even eating alone.
Attached to an appetizing lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even manages to smile, speaks to strangers who work around him, bring him his medicine, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My biggest wish is for me to be cured of diarrhea, it's humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man is pissing on his feet," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at the house of Victor-Gadbois.
Regressing at the child's stage, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
"It depends on the person's ability to accept regression," he notes.
Because, in the opinion of many people working in palliative care, great moments are taking place at the very heart of this regression.
Patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
They have a life prognosis of up to three months.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer provides so-called "curative" care.
For Mrs. A., 89, the worst fear is to die "conscious and suffocated".
But the disease made me discover my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no more wishes in life," she said, before accepting a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days, however, she is waiting for a last visit from her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, with a group of volunteers, body care and food aid are provided.
It is palliative care, which is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 people.
It's very little when you know you all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, says Dr.Christiane Martel, one of the home's doctors.
Whether in terms of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
If you're dying, you'll be willing to take care of your mouth with brandy or Pepsi, depending on your request.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night, Mr. X was served a beer, who died during the night.
This morning, his son will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help loved ones as much as patients," says Nathalie Savard, Director of Care.
At the house of Victor-Gadbois, the days follow each other but do not resemble each other.
Along with an old 93-year-old man who enjoyed his last family assembly in the courtyard, well-sheltered in his pillows while being toasted in his honour, a 36-year-old man tragically died, surrounded by his parents, his wife and two young children, after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, there are still three to five beds that are occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients who are admitted to the house Victor-Gadbois arrive from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
Problems with access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal stage of his or her life, whether at home, in hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec's health care that makes many palliative care physicians fear the adoption of legislation governing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care leaders including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec's health care system is not strong enough to ensure that everyone is entitled to quality palliative care before they agree to proceed with euthanasia.
Recently, she said, I saw a patient spend 14 days in emergency, in great pains, without being taken care of.
I'm afraid patients are only asking to die because they don't get the proper care.
And at the same time, several oncologists work on their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Hélène Richard's life expectancy was already minimal when she dropped out of hard chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she told me.
But she told me I was done!
Not all-powerful care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for not having responded to their request after they have been relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, Director of Palliative Care at the Society of Home Palliative Care in Greater Montreal, patients would be resistant to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which amounts to sleeping the patient until his or her death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
Sick people who are not relieved always say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But it doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to euthanize me", it means "I want to be relieved".
