We began to focus on the issues of reproduction in space by focusing on flora.
Half a century ago, we were experimenting with plants.
Four generations of small peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from the Earth's varieties.
Then we put insects, small, reproductive drosophilic flies into orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent to space to see how an embryo was developing in weightlessness.
At the exit, we get a completely normal chick.
Then the problems begin.
"The problem is related to the fact that the chick has to find a support, he has to stand on his feet and start moving," explains the director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical-Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IPB) Vladimir Sychev.
By finding no support, the chicks were agitated in a disorderly way.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophying.
The chicks did not react to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die after four days.
"We have scarred their eyes twice, then we have given up, because it is simply impossible to work with them there," explains Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of the experiment with the chicks in space.
The last biological "miniature arch" with animals was sent to orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, the "Bion" biosatellite will only carry species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetuses into space.
In principle, nothing supernatural has been discovered.
