The head of the ISC (Superior Institution for the Control of Public Finances) said: "the control of pseudo self-employment (in Czech " Švarc system") failed because of politicians.
In the area of public procurement, the Czech Republic has competent inspectors and high-quality legislation, but it is lagging behind in its implementation.
This was stated by Miloslav Kala, Vice-President of the Supreme Audit Institution in an interview for Aktuálně.cz.
"The law will never be perfect, but its application must be fair and, in my opinion, that is what is lacking in us," Kala said in his comment on the current situation.
A joint inspection by Czech and German inspectors also suggests similar conclusions.
He cites as an example of abusive practice Petr Nečas' approach to the "Švarc system".
Mr. Prime Minister recently said that the ODS was not going to bother contractors with controls, so is it allowed or prohibited?
"The law must be applied in one way or another, so if it forbids something, even the head of government cannot prevent an inspection authority from acting to demand compliance with the law," Kala says.
At the meeting of the supervisory committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you mentioned a Czech-German project in which the public procurement laws of these two countries were compared.
What was the concrete question?
This is a parallel control that we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation provides for how to manage public procurement and specific national legislation and a practice itself follow it.
We have gathered all this together and although this monitoring procedure has not yet been completed, very interesting differences have appeared to us: generally speaking, our legislation is perhaps "more severe and of better quality", however, according to certain parameters, practice as such is better in Germany.
This confirms, therefore, that it is not enough to continuously develop more and more detailed rules but that it is necessary to devote itself to the very implementation of the law.
How can this project help you concretely and what does it result for you?
A common control of this kind should contribute precisely to the end of our efforts to clarify the laws, to lower and improve the thresholds, when this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means getting the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and any criminal activity.
But lowering market thresholds will not necessarily achieve this goal.
It may be that this system is so overwhelmed by red tape that those who seek its faults will find much more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
You are talking about internal problems concerning the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system in Germany work?
Is there an institution similar to our SAI or a different method of organization?
As far as the institutions, like the SAI, operate there the Bundesrechnungshof which is organised similarly, it also has a council constituted a little differently, but these two institutions basically proceed in a similar way .
The competences are also, to a certain extent, similar, however, with a nuance in relation to our system: Germany is a federal structure, so it also has such courses of accounts at the level of the various Länder.
The ORH can only control federal money, which corresponds to the resources of the state.
The public funds managed at home by the regions and the municipalities, are controlled there at the level of the Länder's accounts.
As far as national legislation is concerned, is it simpler than ours?
I would not like to make a general comparison without concrete data, however, in some areas Germany is often referred to as a model, but it certainly cannot be said that it does better in all areas.
Maybe it's because they have better detectives?
No, certainly not, but I repeat, I don't have any comparison data.
However, it must also be said that this country, which we regard as a model, is also facing a whole range of problems.
Otherwise they wouldn't have any advantage in cooperating with our institution, would they?
As far as national legislation is concerned, what has been meant for you, as an institution, by the amendment of the law on public procurement, has its effect already been felt?
As this amendment has entered into force relatively recently, it does not yet have an impact on our control operations.
As we carry out post-checks, we have to count with a certain delay.
