Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as a twentieth member of the Agency, it is the second member State of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and in subsequent years participated in a number of Agency projects.
However, the road from Poland to space began much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles worked on space flights; they did not always meet with understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, A. Šternfeld's lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, at which he presented ideas from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold and years later Šternfeld remembered that only Dr.Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934 Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his book "Introduction à l'astronautique".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a propagator of the world-renowned astronautic, his contribution was rewarded in particular by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters of the hidden face of the Moon.
As early as 1925, a train was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket should be used to propell or brake the draisin.
The only known information about this draisine is that of the press of the time.
Starting in 1933, Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was carried out by Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
The records show that this research had reached the testing stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search stopped.
In 1937, plans for a photoelectric hunting rocket, designed by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects were for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all plans for the use of rocket technology were led by the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee had been established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war put an end to its activities.
After the war, further work on aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, one company is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the Problem newspaper, which contains four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a company dedicated to Astronautics
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the international Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and as early as autumn, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Starting in 1956, PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This 1800-metre range rocket was 80 cm long and weighed just under 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version, RM-1A, was built, and during the summer of 1959, two-stage RM-2 rocket flight tests were started in the Bledov Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 metres long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeded the first RM rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B, and -1C) were developed; they distinguished themselves by the dimensions of space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 litres, while in Meteor-1B it was 0.34 litres and in Meteor-1C it was 0.62 litres.
The maximum range of all these types of gear was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the Aeronautical Institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of approximately 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were later built.
Mention should also be made of Poland's entry into the Committee for Space Research (COSPAR) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Under the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, the Miroslaw Hermaszewski pilot became, after Vladimír Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this programme.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the Public Works Act.
This decision raised a lively debate in public opinion.
It is undoubtedly interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Economic systems oriented towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This means in concrete terms that the different economic entities and national economic systems are constantly in conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of free trade and free movement (without limits) of private capital combined with unbridled financial speculation.
The considerable differences in labour prices (wages) give rise to price pressure.
The following meaning must be put to the end: a producer tries to resist economic competition by importing low-priced goods by making the competitor's price "more expensive", with the aim of removing a greater share of the market and thus increasing its own profits.
On a large scale, this means that most entrepreneurs either transfer production abroad or buy at low prices or disappear. The result is high unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social and hence no responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the State's social security contributions are necessarily increasing.
This whole situation intensifies the perfect unwillingness of businessmen to pay taxes and thus to compensate for the economic and social damage caused to society as a whole by this race for profit.
This situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
Unscrupulous practices of private capital create a situation in the different economies in which the governments of the different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to their homes.
In other words, governments put their own people at the mercy of private capital without taking into account social collapse.
This is mainly reflected in the amendments to existing laws.
The aim is to compel its own population economically to accept the diktat of private capital prices, particularly in the area of wages.
This is due, on the one hand, to a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and, on the other hand, to the restriction of employees' rights in the field of labour legislation.
This results in increasing poverty and deepening the differences between the rich and the poor.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, for years there have been public food distribution points for the poor who cannot support themselves with their own work.
There are already millions of these people.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it is becoming quite common for employees to receive such wages that the state is forced to pay a supplement so that they reach the minimum subsistence level.
Such a scandal has, for example, been brought up to date in the case of employees working as auxiliaries to the federal parliament.
The economic measures of virtually all the Member States of the southern EU undoubtedly create a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the nineteenth century) or to live with poverty wages, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day private capital will invest in their country.
The question here is: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will change from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or then a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turkish, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European wage.
This also applies to the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media argue that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the directed economy leads to an economic disaster.
Private capital strongly supports the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory intervention.
We must then ask ourselves whether private capital does not influence and, even, does not control today, according to its own selfish interests, politics and by the same, the entire state.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The proof is that there is a virtually all-powerful lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation in the area of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is condemnable but not punishable.
In the Federal Republic of Germany, the situation is such that due to the lack of financial resources, the national ministries delegate the drafting of legislation to law firms closely linked to the industry.
These bills are then adopted in the Bundestag.
The totality of power does not come from the people, as Western-style constitutions say, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that liberalist democracies are now quickly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Time of Caesar and Pompey": "The state had long been in disrepair and functions were attributed by violence.
The bribes, the favours obtained illegally, and the stones and swords were also used to obtain these posts.
The lower-tables and corruption would proliferate without limits and the people would go to the elections with votes already sold" ... ... "The honest people were not looking for office, it resulted once the state remained 8 months without consuls". ... "It was really beginning to say that the remedy to this difficult situation was an autocracy and that it was necessary to choose an energetic man" ... It is true that Appianos had in mind Pompey, but it was Caesar who irreversibly transformed democracy into an absolutist regime.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, the present society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard for the interest of society as a whole.
In its essence, private capital is no longer capable of understanding and promoting the interests of society as a whole.
Today, as in the past, the result is a decadence without previous elites, without any effort to carry out profound reforms.
We must therefore seek the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
In the present state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of liberal democracies can be seen as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites are completely unaware of the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, the humanitarian and social crises we witness today, and the crimes against humanity as we know them in ancient and recent history.
The repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under pressure from economic competition, both at the international level and at the European level, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to seek ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution consists of socio-political reforms, which will strengthen the State's capital investment in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the position of monopoly of private capital in society for the benefit of the State.
