The Argo movie: when everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of Islamist students stormed the American embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, who had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the American administration a positive outcome, it could not abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously undermined the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to secure the release of the hostages.
It was a hard blow to the prestige of the United States, further aggravated by the fiasco of the attempt to free the hostages by force.
The sequestered diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate in the United States created a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment.
The Iranian debacle strongly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered America a small victory.
Just before she was busy, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated events, they found themselves in the residence of the Ambassador of Canada.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran with a rocky cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a film crew who came to make scouts for the shooting of a science fiction film.
Genre combination
The plan of the expert in exfiltration Tony Mendez required the collaboration of Hollywood.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized magazines reported on this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
On the one hand, it is a political thriller conceived in a realistic way but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful blow, of a treachery - like, for example, in the trilogy Ocean's eleven, Twelve and Thirteen.
The atmospheres follow each other: documentary-style Tehran sequences (in the subtitled sequences are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and the way in which, thanks to these photos, these same situations were transcribed in the film, there are no great differences),
lighter Hollywood passages, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
And then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director and his acting game stopped generating ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the dark police officer "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It's also Affleck's first film that doesn't take place in his home town, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where Tehran's role "is held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive by its clarity which also suggests confusion and unpredictability occurring when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators get a similar effect in fictional scenes (the fake shooting team in Tehran's bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to settle for a subject that actually offered few thrilling scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
He is doing very well, he sometimes adds some elements to reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is ruled out by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the airstrip is quite drawn by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in its dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events in too many different places.
If it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood co-operators, their characters would have deserved a larger place and they are not, far from that, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, he lets himself be seen with moderate interest, enjoying the realization and retro style of the 70's.
It leads the viewer, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story still, in a certain way, unfinished to date, and as an illustration of the exaggerated nature of the representation of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the job.
Rules to inflate balloons, bananas and circus
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which conducts an annual public inquiry into the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to launch the competition for the regulation or ideas from the most absurd "EU workshop".
"The fact that the EU has recently planned to adopt a quota of 40 per cent of women for the management of large European companies has been at the root of our decision," said the press freedom organisation, Patrik Nacher, for the Právo newspaper.
Among the absurdities mentioned are already, for example, the recent decision of the European Court to unify insurance premiums for men and women.
So far, however, women have been advantaged in terms of life insurance rates because they represent, objectively, a lesser risk to insurance companies.
People can report until the end of the year any other such incredible idea of "the EU workshop".
"The vote will take place before the end of February 2013", informed Nacher.
Among the controversial EU regulations are, for example, the requirement to add organic components to fuels, which has adverse environmental consequences, or the ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers, solely because they contain a relatively small amount of a hazardous substance, or the Directive on the size of hens' cages, which has led to an increase in egg prices.
Criticism has also been expressed in the past against the de facto ban on the use of the term "butter to spread" or the withdrawal of the sale of conventional light bulbs.
Quality bananas must have a size of 14 centimeters.
The European administration often reacts under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby whose demands are usually defended in Brussels by a state or group of states (for example, the Czech Republic is currently imposing the demands of its banks by threatening to use its veto power).
The interests of pressure groups are also at the root of the fact that bananas in the Union must not be less than 14 cm in size or have an "abnormal curve".
The European Commission defended itself by arguing that it was only harmonising non-homogeneous national standards that complicated trade.
The standards for fruit and vegetables have been relaxed despite opposition from some States, claiming that the existing directives result in a waste of food.
The first prize may be awarded in this survey to last year's EU Regulation which requires a warning on inflatable balloons that children under the age of 8 must not inflate without adult surveillance.
The EU referred to an American survey according to which balloons are, among toys, the leading cause of death of children by suffocation.
A similar restriction applies to children under the age of 14 when blowing in fair trumpets.
We have some weird ideas in our house too.
The following rule concerning European officials themselves is quite absurd: because of the sensitivity of this topic to Greece, anyone with an official position in the EU cannot use the name "Macedonia" and should instead speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The Bankovnípoplatky.com server, in collaboration with the "Let Do" association of liberal economists, has named in this survey, in addition to certain absurdities mentioned above, the Union Regulation on the volume of food reserves in the territory of the Czech Republic.
The EU had set maximum volumes for food supplies that could be on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic then, for example, removed the volumes fixed for canned mushrooms and, as a result, risked a heavy fine.
The organisers of this survey found it interesting to pay money to some countries because they do not have access to the sea and to grant a grant to apply for grants.
These ideas, however, are not from Brussels but from Prague.
"The fact that we don't have a sea handicaps us.
We are going to ask the European Union for a refund." Thus, in autumn 2004, the Minister of Agriculture of the time Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) spoke.
He argued that, as a result of our wheat production, and as a result of so-called "interventionist" purchases, the state had found itself with full stocks that it had to export.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us millions of euros, because the Czech Republic is far from ports.
In the end, the European Commission responded positively to Czech demand and organised a call for tenders for the purchase of wheat from countries without maritime access.
Grants for grants were proposed to municipalities by the Ministry of Local Development headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), which were to be used in concrete terms to prepare applications for grants granted by Brussels.
The EU says: "Weird regulations are rare".
While the regulations often give rise to criticism in the Member States, according to many experts, the EU's efforts to regulate and improve the effectiveness of the functioning of the Union as well as in the field of its general development are rather commendable.
More serious, for example, is, according to experts, the problem of using EU grants for projects that have absolutely nothing to do with strengthening European integration, but which were imposed by the Member States during the budgetary negotiations.
The fact that the Czech Republic, like other EU countries, has to fight in Brussels for the right to use specific names for these traditional products (a struggle that it does not always win) arouses strong emotions among Czechs.
If at the end of six years of battle against Germans and Austrians, the Czechs successfully defended the name "Olomoucké tvar+ky", for what of the name "Tuzemský rum" that dates back to us in the nineteenth century, our producers had to replace it with the name "Tuzemák".
