The architects of the MVRDV firm prove that the real adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To be convinced of this, it is enough to contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it's very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist in a large neighboring company, tells us: "Yes, it is indeed beautiful, this building".
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one goes of their own free will to one of these ringuard libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeping town that has nothing attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The municipality of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore some neurons to the brains, the city decided a few years ago to contribute to the general culture and reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro notes in the form of pretty small miniatures of painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city's authorities realized that there was only one way to take control of statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, of the architect's office in Rotterdam MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of buildings full of mind and often cynical, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and presented himself to the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a ricination on the face.
And while the members of the jury were still looking at each other, disconcerted and shrugging their shoulders, Maas, beating him, stacked his choice books in order of size to make them a pyramid, and ended his speech supported by militant arguments by a: "common heart!"
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the €30 million mountain sprang from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and a few adjoining buildings and houses for a total of 50 dwellings.
At the beginning of November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, this dull little town, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and a town hall of a staggering ugliness, whose white facades invite to think that they are home to a dairy, has been enriched by a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Path to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Certainly, an elevator transports you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open to you when you walk the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior made entirely of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and the elegant reverbers speak unequivocally the language of the municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We're already looking at public benches, dogs and little boys and girls playing ball.
And all over books, books, and more books.
"Normally, the library shelves are located along the façade and in the middle there is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," explains Willy Maas.
We completely changed the classical spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from inside to outside.
The interior of the mountain of books has been skillfully designed: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the centre for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes panelling, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircase ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the architects and engineers of the hardened building do not want unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager in Spijkenisse municipality, in response to the Standard.
One day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in a Frisian farm.
In the Netherlands, for years synthetic membranes of one millimetre thickness have been used as substrates in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and you save time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into four centimetres thick plates.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and transforms into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 meters, the literary café offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and potted ficus.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to maintaining the ideal level of humidity of the air of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the new soul
"It's incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in the field of ecology," says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is controlled by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is below a glass bell, the sun only illuminates the interior for a short time, even on days of fine weather.
The thick wooden beams mounted across the glass façade serve as a sunshield, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
Fully automated blinds handle the rest.
Stefan Spemron, the above-mentioned septic computer scientist, has already ventured to enter the new library.
Lisette Verhaig too was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as "the soul finally recovered" from Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his or her personal library.
This has made it possible to fill the voids of the library which was not yet fully stocked (today, it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from all sides.
For architect Winy Maas, "there's nothing worse than a half-empty library."
"I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration."
This is how MVRDV has achieved the master discipline called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
Even though she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role."
Germany chose abstention in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert on relations between the US and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian request for observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must exercise caution, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but was not too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 insurgency in Libya, Germany also chose to abstain in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany find it difficult to take a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so to speak defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore clashed with several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to find this role, but are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Great Britain
What, then, does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for the Germans?
It shows a willingness to adopt positions that are independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position with regard to the conflict in the Middle East and abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to clash with public opinion, but also with the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a determining factor.
However, I would not place too much emphasis on it, because it is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is at least a determining factor in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany undermine its relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I believe that the fracture is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States has announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do the views differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing a great deal of understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the true differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you observe the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from overflowing with enthusiasm for Netanyahu's policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think it makes things easy for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
They cannot therefore fit within a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
That is what they are doing now on the issue of the euro.
In my view, Germany will assume a role as a locomotive in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This question has always been a delicate one.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware of the fact that they must play a role that is more important to their independence.
Does Germany see itself as an important player on the international stage, does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or does she still have difficulties taking on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is still uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still has difficulties playing a more important role.
If we look, for example, at the euro crisis, we notice that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make things easy for the Germans.
In fact, it's always the same problem: we don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
She has to deal with a wide variety of neighbours and opinions, and it's not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is only diminishing, but at the moment the EU does not fill this void, so who remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant and if they're less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America work together to analyse the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German policy, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Trademark Protection" in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well-known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is it really about?
Behind this name is an officially registered trademark in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys protection such that the undertaking bearing its name cannot lodge a complaint.
And even if she could, it is not certain that she would win the case.
"It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their brands in China," explains Thomas Pattloch, lawyer for Taylor Wessing, a law firm specializing in violation of property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Imitators need only a few additional letters to register their trademarks.
So instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sports goods.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet in which the registrations made at the Beijing Trademark Office are located.
On 14 September 2010, a Chinese company filed the trade mark Zegna DF Puma, a name that the company artificially created by appropriating part of the name of Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a well-known fact that the Chinese have become world champions of copying and infringement of intellectual property.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping centres that sell virtually only counterfeits.
However, Pattloch's cases are different: his constituents instruct him to address the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese speak of "Bang Mingpai", a parent brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is with this term that women who marry rich men are designated.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to blame for.
"It's bad for business, we have to fight this trend," demands Pattloch.
"The brand is sweetened, the singularity disappears, the damage to the reputation is enormous."
The financial losses and legal costs are in millions for the sectors concerned, especially with regard to expensive flagship products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, China represents, with an annual volume of 15 billion euros, the third world market for luxury products and the fastest growing one.
However, it is not easy to remove questionable registrations from the trademark register and these procedures are expensive.
These can last up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch refers to the trials in which the court rejected the complaint, because after a long period of time the name criticized had become a "market reality".
Pattloch explains that if the complainant is not lucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarist because he would have harmed his brand in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler had lost a legal battle against the builder of the Sany construction machine, the same company that had just bought the producer of Putzmeister concrete pumps.
That's why the Chinese can use an emblem that looks like the Mercedes star.
Geely, Volvo's acquirer, used before a blue and white logo reminiscent of BMW's. The conflict was settled and Geely had to modify it.
The fashion house Lacoste had lost against the plagiarists of Hong Kong and Singapore who had reoriented the gaze of the famous crocodile in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
However, the CTMO trademark office in Beijing admits to having experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, the Office would have passed last year from an "emergency situation in the course of work to a recovered normality".
Thus, the number of unprocessed opposition proceedings would have decreased by 22%.
Almost 57,000 such cases were reportedly closed, an increase of 75% over the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81,500 proceedings remain outstanding at the Office.
It's expensive to act
As is often the case in China, the figures are impressive.
Last year, CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the Board, this is a record and this means that China is for the tenth consecutive time at the top of the ranking for the number of new deposits in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal marks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the Office would have recorded 1.8 billion yuan of registration fees.
In other words, each record has averaged 1.280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as illustrated by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting against a Chinese plagiarist.
Of course, the Germans were able to get the illegal manufacture of vehicle components suspended.
However, the imitator was able to maintain its Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
"It's our fault, because family names cannot be protected in Germany," says Hanno Wentzler, CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The trade mark office had therefore rejected the objection of the Munichers.
Freudenberg has certainly won the case in the following two instances, but the opposing side continues to fight until today.
Vigilance is on the table.
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, he believes in a positive outcome of the trial and boasts the professionalism of the judges.
Nevertheless, he adds: "the procedure is long, difficult and we cost a lot of time and money."
It is also difficult to estimate internal costs. The archives department has even had to review the actions of the last 100 years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg had even unsuccessfully proposed to the opposing party a "big six-digit euro amount" to settle the dispute.
"This is what we see for us," Wentzler says.
The dangers of the Far East threaten even to overflow into Europe.
This would be the case if imitators in this region were to ensure the exploitation of unprotected marks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to register Freudenberg in Germany for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long abandoned this sector, but it could still prevent the deposit.
Wentzler adds: "vigilance is in order."
Pattloch and advise German companies to exercise great caution in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, in their view, to rely on international trademark law, foreigners should rather "register also in China everything that is likely to be protected", as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, costs may be much higher than registration costs.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle in the last act of its legal drama, the company would have to pay licence fees to the opposing party for the use of its own name, as Wentzler explains.
Or we would lose our place in the segment of the market in question.
