The trip to the Talysh Mountains is a long romantic journey.
At the turn of the many turns of the road, the small bus cahoots along forested hills, torrential rivers and modest farms.
Everything is green and fertile, it's almost like the Black Forest.
But here we are in the deep south of Azerbaijan, the border with Iran is only a few kilometres away.
This is where the Caucasian ethnic group, called Talysh, lives, about which we do not know much, except that they speak perfectly Persian and Azeri and that they have a very long life.
Terminus: Lerik.
The small town plastrons with its too aggressive architecture of the Soviet era that does not at all agree with the picturesque mountain landscape.
European tourists are rare here, the journey from the capital of Azerbaijan, Baku, is far too painful.
It takes eight hours to travel 323 kilometres, because the road has only one lane.
The province has not yet benefited from the legendary wealth the country owes to its oil reserves in the Caspian Sea.
However, 48-year-old Pilata Fatulayeva is convinced that Lerik has the potential to become a tourist destination.
"Bakou became famous in May with the help of Eurovision, and next year there will be the festival of the oldest people in the world here," explains Fatulayeva.
She is the director of the museum of longevity, the only museum of this kind in the world.
We can discover the lives of about eight dozen Talysh of the region who are more than 100 years old. Fatulayeva shows us a black and white photo.
This is my grandfather. He's 120 years old.
Have one more child at 136 years
But the controversial star of the museum is Şirali Müslümov, a shepherd who would have been 168 years old.
However, there is no birth certificate.
And when one thinks that the oldest documented person was 122 years old, Müslümov's age seems more than dubious.
"He was born in 1805 in this region, he died in 1973," says Fatulayeva.
The man would have married three times and had 23 children. At the age of 136, he would still have conceived a daughter.
Would Şirali Müslümov have been wrong for a few decades in calculating his age?
Rembrandt Scholz, a gerontologist at the Max-Planck Institute in Rostock, has also heard of man in the great age of Central Asia.
"Amazingly old people also live in parts of China, Japan or the Hunza Valley in Pakistan," Scholz explains, "in Sardinia too, there are men who live incredibly old."
However, it is impossible to establish scientific evidence due to the lack of documentation, and there was no civil registry.
Every day, a glass of melted butter
It is, however, true that people in the Lerik area often reach an age worthy of the Bible patriarchs.
Currently, 20 people are over 100 years old.
What, then, is the reason for longevity in the south of this country?
Farid Mugimzadeh, the Azeri tourist guide, explains that the Talysh have special genes.
On the other hand, Fatulayeva, the museum director, thinks it's a matter of food.
However, it does not seem plausible, from a nutritional point of view, that the high-calorie meals of the Talysh, who like meat, bread and especially dairy products and many of which drink a glass of melted butter daily, are good for health.
Or is it the simple way of life that preserves the youth of people? In Cengemiran, a tiny village near the city of Lerik, lives Rubaba Mirzayeva.
At age 97, she is still relatively young for the region.
Mirzayeva, who claims to have 143 descendants, lives in a modest wooden house, as it is typical to see throughout the Caucasus region.
She sits on the floor next to a baritone, whose contents she beat tirelessly.
Eight people live here under one roof, including one of Mirzayeva's sons and a daughter, who have long been adults.
Two little kids smack in the house too.
In the kitchen, tea is prepared for guests served in typical Armadus glasses in the shape of a belly.
Mirzayeva's white teeth are perfectly aligned, and under his scarf hide long braids of a dark blond that his son proudly reveals to us.
I've always washed my hair with milk, and that's how I never lost them and they kept their color.
"I never used shampoo," Mirzayeva adds.
