Norway's rakfisk: is it the most fragrant fish in the world?
The five million people living in Norway enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe, but also in the world.
Could the secret of the country's success be linked to local appetite for an extremely fragrant fish?
Have some advanced cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of wet and dirty soccer clothes.
Wait a week.
And you get the disturbing smell of rakfisk, one of Norway's most popular dishes.
I'm in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
It snows, the landscape is spectacular - and this smell, omnipresent, permeates the air.
The rakfisk consists of trout sprinkled with salt and fermented in water for a period of time - depending on the smell you want it to exhale - which can last up to a year.
When the darkness settles and it's cold, Norwegians gather in mass to attend a festival that takes place here in Fagernes, dedicated to this incredible culinary specialty.
"You eat raw, then you swallow a glass of aquavit," explains Havard Halvarsen, a full-time local firefighter who is also known as "Rakfisk General", responsible for managing the festival.
Around us, people get small pieces of fish and a lot of drink.
"Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk," Havard adds.
The drink kills the smell.
I'm trying a few pieces.
If you can avoid getting it under your nose, it's not bad - it reminds you of a sushi that would have spent long hours on a bus.
The rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, before the invention of refrigeration, the fish was immersed in airtight water barrels, then salted in autumn.
Then, during the winter, when well fermented, the fish came out and - without a doubt with the senses diminished by alcohol - eaten.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country to find work, mainly emigrating to the United States.
At present, the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by full employment, high wages and a comprehensive health system.
The Swedes, their old rivals whose country was not so much richer than Norway, cross the border to come to work.
The rakfisk is considered to be something important, a vital though smelling element of Norway's past.
This is one of the most expensive dishes.
But everything is expensive - a small pint of beer or a sandwich will cost you 10 € each.
Norway does not often talk about it in international news, which is not to displease it.
Here, people are unwilling to talk about Anders Breivik, the right-wing extremist racist who shot 77 people, including women and children.
When they talk about this killing, they talk about the "July 22 incident."
Norwegians find it difficult to accept that in their peaceful country one of them may have committed such an act of barbarism.
Since the early 1970s, Norway has owed its wealth to its oil and gas industry, one of the largest in the world.
"But oil is not the unique reason for our success," explains Anna, our waitress, with blonde hair and the eyes of a piercing blue, the image of Nordic well-being, with a rakfisk tray by hand.
We are - how do you say - cautious people.
His English, like most people who live here, is perfect.
We're discreet, we don't like to be noticed.
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution - everything, with the exception of a small percentage of money from this industry, is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
When other countries threw money out of the window, in the years that led us to the international financial crisis, Norway was able to keep its purse tight.
"As long as we can ski in winter and hike in summer, we are happy," says Anna.
"Not to mention the rakfisk," she adds in a carefree laughter.
I stand under the snow and line up to buy something to eat - I got my dose of rakfisk.
On the menu, a burger made of elk, a real discovery, is excellent.
But tonight, the smell of fish is everywhere.
The hotel I stay in is one of many places where we serve rakfisk for dinner and where we can vote for the best of them - or perhaps for the most fragrant of them.
There's a TV show where the presenter wears a papillon knot, surrounded by rakfisk plates.
It's like the Eurovision contest.
"What score did you give the best fish in the Thor-Juergen mountains?"
"Here are our points, Havard."
We hear laughter and applause.
A man falls out of his chair, perhaps because of the abuse of aquavit.
Or maybe it's because of fish fumes.
Mexican Enrique Pena Nieto has a difficult start.
As incoming President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take office in Mexico, Will Grant, of the BBC, is interested in the difficulties that await him and the expectations of the people, which are many.
Road traffic in Mexico City is currently particularly bad.
