Warnings and photos of diseased organs cover dark green packages that are all identical, regardless of brand
This law came into force in Australia as a world first, the logos and colors were replaced by a dark olive green and horrible photos of sick organs and representations of children and babies whose diseases were caused by their parents' smoking.
Apart from the different photos and health warnings, the only difference between packages, since this Saturday, is the brand name, printed in small characters on all packages.
This is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
The Australian federal government stated that the goal was to deter youth from smoking by eliminating glamour.
Studies have shown that if people have not started smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that they will never start.
"Even when they are very young, children understand the message conveyed by tobacco manufacturers through their brand image," said Federal Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have revealed, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with a princess."
Although Australia has the lowest smoking rate in the world and these changes have little impact on multinational profits, other countries are considering a similar approach.
The tobacco industry has put pressure on this law.
Tobacco manufacturers stated that this would boost the black market, which will make it easier to access cheaper cigarettes.
