Counterfeiters in China and Indonesia will sell far more counterfeit cigarettes on the streets of Australia.
Others stated that this law had boosted their activity.
Sandra Ha from Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, stated that the demand for cigarette cases, including silicone to mask the horrible packaging, has increased sharply two months ago since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco challenged the law and lost in the high court of Australia.
Ha stated that Zico has sold 6,000 to wholesalers and is awaiting stock renewal.
For us, business is good.
The only trouble, experts say, is the popularity of social media and the segment of the population targeted by the plan.
After a series of Australian laws prohibiting commercials on TV, sports sponsorship and the obligation of retailers to conceal cigarettes, tobacco marketing is now available online.
Australia has banned web advertising by local companies and sites, but it cannot prevent foreign sites from doing so.
"If you work in tobacco marketing and have only a small window to promote your products, the Internet is the best place to go," said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman noted an increase in the contributions of some lambda citizens to brands on social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
We have to ask ourselves whether this is a simple citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes and has taken the trouble to make a video, or whether it is a marketing campaign orchestrated by an agency?
British American Tobacco Australia stated that the industry is focused on the new regulations in force rather than on marketing.
