I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulphur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases... to which are obviously added their usual breathing problems, arthroses, pains in the knees and shoulders, distorted by the weight of the baskets.
By balancing the basket on its back, Unainik, 53 years old, can only load 50 kilos.
Every day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulphur from the volcano, which three trucks carry to the warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometres away by a weed-infested goat trail.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life," Unainik says, opening his mouth well, revealing several missing teeth.
The eldest of her five children, aged 30, also works as a carrier of sulphur.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the most difficult jobs in the world: that of the human mules of the Kawah ljen volcano.
