AIDS-related deaths are now due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 when he was confirmed with the HIV test.
"It was as if the sky had fallen on my head," he said, referring to the time of the announcement, that the doctor had tried to make "less painful", in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness on his own and began to find out about him and his hard work was such that he had just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), in which he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, where there were many doubts, few treatment choices and more stigma.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he was speechless."
In those days, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their disease, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "exhausted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the onset of AIDS in the world, in all cases after the first reported cases, "the great victory is today that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the right time and the survival of the population in general is exactly the same", said the head of the HIV unit of the HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva and he takes as reference that this information was validated in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
HIV/AIDS infectiologist and expert, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a life-threatening disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depends on the level of affective immune system of patients at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years for CD4 levels of 200 and up to 50 years for those who reach 500 CD4 levels.
To put it simply, this means that for someone who would receive a positive HIV diagnosis at age 25, "as long as he remains under control, he will be able to live without problems up to 75 years", explained the scientist interviewed.
In order to put this progress in context, it is important to know that the life expectancy of Mexicans is now 76 years on average.
While it is true that mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died as a result of AIDS has increased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the UNAIDS annual report), but it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60% of the patients identified on the national data basis have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths until May of this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
Then why are there still deaths?
I don't think the problem comes from access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
Over the past 12 years at least, we've never missed drugs, the problem is that patients come to very advanced stages because they don't know they're infected, or they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
It gives us an indisputable fact "nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have opportunistic infection, what it takes to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to carry out earlier diagnoses and, for that, to offer massive screening tests, to all those who ask for it".
The experts and members of the State Council for AIDS Prevention in Jalisco (Coesida) agree with his proposal, as do the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to do his test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and, despite his young age, he was already carrying AIDS and suffering from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you learn that you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and don't want to know anything.
"If I'm going to die, it's better if I have three times a week," they say, "I don't.
The change has been beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medication.
To date, his parents only know that he is suffering from cancer.
I have a normal life, just like anyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I pay attention to myself and to the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, thanks to his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the march of World AIDS Day.
Let them do the test, if they have taken risks, the sooner they will know if they are HIV-positive and the better it will be, and if they already have the diagnosis, they must know that we can live like everyone else, being responsible.
His message sums up the slogan of the battle against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programmes and the ordinary citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara journalist who has embraced the cause of HIV.
And the biggest is prevention.
In all the places dedicated to this, "the distribution of condoms has actually been increased, before we were given one or two, now we are given packages of a hundred, it is very good, but it results, that still today, some do not have access to condoms", he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
The question: "What are you going to do with it?", asked with sarcasm and value judgments by social workers, guidance counsellors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that teenagers do not want to hear, says the journalist.
It proposes to reorient this inefficient distribution; that condoms not only be sold at counters, but be found in public toilet dispensers and in places where young people attend.
It is not about encouraging promiscuity.
Nor was it a question of paying the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González had said when asked whether there would be a distribution of condoms in his administration.
"This is not how sexuality works, the best is to provide condoms to people already sexually active," he stressed.
The figures in Jalisco
There are 13.435 cumulative cases (12.158 of AIDS and 1.317 of HIV).
The State is the fourth largest state in the country in terms of the number of new and cumulative cases of AIDS and the 13th largest in terms of the number of HIV patients.
92% of the contamination occurs by sex, 6% by blood and 2% by perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV, since for each recorded case, there are 4 or 5 people who do not know.
A judgment ratified on appeal by a United States court ignores the restructuring of the Vitro Group’s debt through commercial bankruptcy in Mexico. The scenario sets a bad precedent for all domestic companies with ramifications in the neighbouring country and with solvency problems.
It therefore seems that the procedures for the survival of societies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the country with a starry banner, contrary to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the judgement handed down on 15 June by Judge Harlin Hale of the Court of Bankruptcy for the North District of Texas leaves Mexican companies defenceless in the face of the possibility of embargoing their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico's main glass manufacturer to appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court on the basis of three inconsistencies.
First, while the trial judge states that creditors must register under the United States Bankruptcy Act, the Fifth Circuit Appeal Court, based in New Orleans, states that the main proceeding is formalized commercial bankruptcy in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing international procedural cooperation in insolvency cases of companies with a transnational profile.
Indeed, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of International Commercial Law had been created for that purpose by taking the American Law Institute as arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment establishes that without the intercompany vote, recognised in the critical mass of commercial bankruptcy, the debts contracted by Vitro's subsidiaries towards the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
In fact, Vitro's case is not the first to use this plan.
Here there are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose debts were guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Commercial Bankruptcy.
Moreover, what is certain is that, since there remained the votes of the subsidiaries, in any case Vitro's creditors who fought against this in the courts of the United States, that is to say the "vulture" funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have obtained the majority.
The vote would have been 45 to 37.
A data omitted by the appellate court.
On the other hand, Vitro has been blamed for the difficult situation he has faced since 2008 without stopping at the serious economic crisis facing the United States, passing on costs to the country.
For the time being, the González Sada family society will appeal to the same appeal court to have the vote taken in its entirety, i.e. with the five magistrates, since only three had voted.
The insurance remedy will demand non-prosperity and requires a review of the trial by a higher court, in this case the Supreme Court of Justice of the United States.
The most serious is that the court ignored a document sent by the Government of Mexico on behalf of the amicus curiae ("court friend") in which Vitro's procedure under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act was detailed, pointing out that it freed him from the agreements signed by the two countries to bring it to the same level as paragraph 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Act.
In addition, he pointed out that the country had adhered to the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules established for cross-border insolvency cases, which guaranteed fairness for debtors and creditors.
