A course dealing with the "End of the World" has just begun
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion teacher Stuart Charmé decided to give a lecture on the end of the world, he knew that he was throwing there an irresistible hook: the end of the "big count" of the Mayan calendar, on December 21, to which many people refer as proof of the imminent end of the world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what he was waiting for in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax abyss that some dubbed the "Armageddon of Debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where the Christian theorists of the end times thought that the apocalypse would trigger.
"I didn't realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," said Professor Charmé this week to his students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey.
If we look at what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were telling it, it was a very good time.
And it must be remembered that what is evil is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he is not the only teacher to teach about "the end of the world" this semester, which, in theory, will be the last in history.
In Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker gives the course "Media, Culture and End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides some human conduct.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with examples of real life.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible," said Vacker.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply entitled "The End of the World".
"We add "2012" to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world does not disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In Pennsylvania, the final exam will be spent the day before the Apocalypse, which leaves students with no choice but to work "until the very night of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The courses have proved quite popular.
"It was complete in two hours," Restall said about his course for high-level students, made up of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the start of the semester from people who asked if there was room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves," says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, University of Rutgers-Camden.
For the fear of Revelation, whether secular or religious, is only a question of comfort, or of lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in Psychology and Infirmary, claims to have watched all apocalyptic films.
